{{Infobox person | name = Chan Chor Khine | nationality = Burmese-Chinese | birth_date = 1886 <ref name="Butler">{{cite book | title=Who's Who in Burma: under the distinguished patronage of HE Sir Harcourt Butler|last=Butler |first=Harcourt |year=1927|publisher=Indo-Burma Publishing Agency}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]] | death_date = {{d-da|April 1934|1886}} | death_place = [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]] | death_cause = Suicide | spouse = Margret von Beck <ref name="Butler"/> | occupation = businessman, land-owner and investor }}
'''Chan Chor Khine''' ({{zh|t=曾祖慨|poj=Chan Chó̍-khài}}; born in [[Rangoon]], [[Burma]]) was a [[Burmese-Chinese]] businessman, land-owner, investor and philanthropist.
==Early life == Chan was born in 1886 to self-made millionaire father [[Chan Mah Phee]] and his mother, the daughter of a Burmese peasant. He attended [[Basic Education High School No. 6 Botataung|St Paul's High School, Rangoon]] before being educated further in China.
==Rangoon== Chan returned to Burma to join his father's business [[Taik Leong]]. The company dealt primarily in oil, rice and tobacco exports. Chan ultimately became manager of the company upon his father's retirement. He served as an honorary magistrate on the board of the [[Corporation of Rangoon]].<ref name="Butler"/>
Chan donated 10 acres of land for the construction of the [[Chinese High School, Rangoon|Chinese High School]] in Rangoon.
==Death== Chan committed suicide in April 1934 at 10:20am by shooting himself in the head at his estate, [[the Brightlands]].
