'''Pavitr Gajaseni''' ({{lang-th|ปวิตร คชเสนี}}, also spelled '''Kachasanee''' 13 October 1932 &ndash; February 2015)<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=คุณแหน: 17 กุมภาพันธ์ 2558|newspaper=Naewna|date=17 February 2015|url=http://www.naewna.com/lady/144969|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> was a Thai businessman and [[Shooting sport|sports shooter]]. He was a great-grandson of Prince [[Kaew Nawarat]] of Chiang Mai. He was a partner and director of Sony Thai Co. Ltd, and was a founding member of the Skeet & Trap Shooting Association of Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.misu.ait.ac.th/NewsAndEvents/ReviewArticle.cfm?ReviewCode=199703&ArticleNo=8|title=Exhibitions|work=AIT Review|publisher=Asian Institute of Technology|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaiclayshooting.com/th/about-us/history|title=ประวัติสมาคมยิงเป้าบินแห่งประเทศไทย|work=Skeet & Trap Shooting Association of Thailand website|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref> He competed at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="SportsRef">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ka/pavitr-kachasanee-1.html |title=Pavitr Kachasanee |accessdate=1 January 2016 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref> He also competed at the [[1974 Asian Games]].<ref name="ISSF">{{cite web |url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHTHAM0000000047 |title=ISSF Portrait of the athlete |accessdate=1 January 2016 |work=ISSF}}</ref>
